<HTML map="$(mapmake)">
  <IF val="$(Theatre.GameID)">
    <TRUE>
      <MAPSET map="$map" index="title" to="$(Theatre.GameBrief)"/>
      <MAPSET map="$map" index="realmurl" to="$(Theatre.RealmURL)"/>
    </TRUE>
    <FALSE>
      <MAPSET map="$map" index="title" to="The Lobby"/>
      <MAPSET map="$map" index="realmurl" to="http://www.skotos.net/MansionGame/images/"/>
    </FALSE>
  </IF>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>$(map.title)</TITLE>
    <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"/>
    <INSERT page="/Theatre/local/style-include.sam"/>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="white" link="red" alink="red" vlink="#2e8b57" BACKGROUND="$(map.realmurl)background.jpg" topmargin="10" leftmargin="10" marginwidth="10" marginheight="10">

<INSERT page="/Theatre/local/logo-include.sam"/>
<h1 align="center">Mastering Chat</h1>
<DIV><a href="starting.sam">Getting Started</a> outlines the basics of communication. You can <if val="$(udat.chatmode)"><true>type in anything you want to say at the command line, or you can </true><false></false></if>use an evocation verb to say things, like $(udat.chatchar)SAY, $(udat.chatchar)TELL, or $(udat.chatchar)SHOUT: <font face="courier" color="#ff33ff">$(udat.chatchar)shout "I said I like cats!"</font> However, $(map.title) allows for much richer levels of
communication.

<P></P><B>OTHER SPEECH VERBS.</B> A number of synonyms for $(udat.chatchar)SAY can be used to communicate. They
represent
different volumes of speech, different emotions, and different contexts.
Verbs
that represent volume include: $(udat.chatchar)SCREAM, $(udat.chatchar)SHOUT, and $(udat.chatchar)WHISPER. Verbs that relate to the
content of a
statement include $(udat.chatchar)ASK, $(udat.chatchar)QUESTION, $(udat.chatchar)STATE, and $(udat.chatchar)TELL.
Verbs that show context in a
conversation
include $(udat.chatchar)COMMENT, $(udat.chatchar)CONTINUE, $(udat.chatchar)REPLY, and $(udat.chatchar)RESPOND.

<P></P><B>OTHER TYPES OF COMMUNICATION.</B> Chat Theatre also allows
you to
attach statements to other types of gestures: like $(udat.chatchar)SMILE, $(udat.chatchar)FROWN, $(udat.chatchar)GRIN, and $(udat.chatchar)SNEER.
Just as with the normal
communication
verbs, you type the gesture and then you type a quoted statement.

<P></P><B>TALKING TO PEOPLE.</B> When you are speaking you can direct
your
statement to a specific person by using the "to" preposition: <FONT
face="courier" color="#ff33ff">$(udat.chatchar)say to cat, "Is your name Chairman Meow?"</FONT>

<P></P><B>USING ADVERBS.</B> You can make your speech more emotionally
appropriate by using adverbs--words like SLOWLY, SADLY, and PRUDENTLY: <font face="courier" color="#ff33ff">$(udat.chatchar)quietly state "That cats are not what they seem."</font> You can
see a list of adverbs starting with a certain letter by typing the verb
you want
to use and then a letter. For example: <font face="courier" color="#ff33ff">$(udat.chatchar)say a</font>.

<P></P><B>MORE INFORMATION.</B> Congratulations! You've gotten started
in $(map.title), and begun the path toward mastering chat. For information on other important topics, type $(udat.chatchar)HELP CLOTHING, $(udat.chatchar)HELP PROXIMITY, and $(udat.chatchar)HELP SKILLS.

<br/>
</DIV>
<INSERT page="/Theatre/local/links-include.sam"/>
</BODY>
</HTML> 

  